Pull_Quotes: I think as a university, a college, a town changes, they should not just come in with bulldozers and clear everything out. I- it’s good to see some of the older buildings that, you know, generations before ours in the early 1900s would have gone to class in, or chapel to worship in, whatever. When you’re into science with library access and stuff like this, you know that the building has to be different to accommodate newer technologies, but the... for the older buildings, modifying them so they’re warmer and more comfortable, but keeping that tradition is a big part, and I’m glad to see that Grinnell has, I think, got a good balance there.

Pull_Quotes: I was a bit homesick. I had come from Jacksonville, Florida; it's 1500 miles away. It was a little bit difficult, and I was a little bit homesick, and I was taking Intro to Political Science, being taught by Wayne Moyer. And I remember at Thanksgiving, he invited those of us who weren't going home for Thanksgiving- invited them out to his house at Rock Creek Lake. And... his wife Helen is a wonderful person, and was a wonderful hostess, and I remember... she fed us in- I don't know, maybe fifteen, twenty of us, and I remember just sitting.... y'know sitting, enjoying the meal, enjoying the- the graciousness and hospitality and looking at Rock Creek Lake in late November... And I remember thinking to myself, you know, "I'm gonna get through this."

Pull_Quotes:
I felt that my professors really served as a mentor to me. I was part of the New Science Project, where we actually- I'm not sure if they still have that today- but we were actually brought on campus a week before everyone's orientation, and it was targeting, like, first-generation students of color.
 And there, I got a chance to meet with some of our professors one-on-one, and.... I felt really connected. So when everyone else showed up, like, it was amazing to have that professor to turn to, and that's the other thing I really cherish about Grinnell, that the professors really reach out to you.

Pull_Quotes: The bathrooms back then- okay, we were very creative. There was one bathroom on a floor, so sometimes there was a dial that went 'Men', 'Women', 'Don't Care', and then of course, in true Grinnell spirit, people would add things to the dial. Okay? 'Dogs', okay, 'Beast', everything. There was one bathroom. Everybody used it. It wasn't a big deal. So- and when people talked about, you know, at other schools, "Oh, there're men on this floor and women on this floor," I'm like, "Whu-oh." You know, Grinnell is way, way past that.

Pull_Quotes: When I had to defend my master's thesis, there was a professor on the committee from another department who was looking over my transcript from Grinnell and so forth, and he commented about, "Well, I see all of these C's," and, "Now here at Emerson you're straight A's. What happened?" And then my thesis advisor said, "Well, you have to remember Grinnell is an exceptional school, and it's much harder to get an A at Grinnell than it would be here at Emerson." And I just sat there and smiled. I was so proud of the school at that moment!

Pull_Quotes: I came as a prospective student in January of 1985, and it was a bitterly cold winter. And I'm form Arkansas, so I didn't really have, like, a winter coat, because we're lucky if we get snow; we got ice occassionally but it really wasn't a big deal. So I land in Des Moines airport with my father, and the pilot gets on the phone- or on the, you know, overhead thing and says, "Well, the temperature here in Des Moines is 29 below with a windchill of 89 below." I thought he was kidding; I didn't think that it really got that cold in the U.S. He wasn't kidding...
